==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hammock
<hw>Ham"mock</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧m"m⟦ocr⟧k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[A word
of Indian origin: cf. Sp. <ets>hamaca</ets>. Columbus, in the Narrative
of his first voyage, says: ⟦ldquo⟧A great many Indians in canoes came to
the ship to-day for the purpose of bartering their cotton, and
<ets>hamacas</ets>, or nets, in which they sleep.⟦rdquo⟧]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A swinging couch or bed, usually made of netting or
canvas about six feet long and three feet wide, suspended by clews or
cords at the ends.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A piece of land thickly wooded, and usually covered
with bushes and vines. Used also adjectively; <as>as, <ex>hammock</ex>
land</as>.</def> <mark>[Southern U. S.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bartlett.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hammock nettings</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>,
<cd>formerly, nets for stowing hammocks; now, more often, wooden boxes
or a trough on the rail, used for that purpose.</cd></cs></p>

<p><ent>Hamous</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Hamose</ent>⟦br⟧
